@lenadunham is everywhere again, thanks to her new memoir, ‘Famesick.’ Fourteen years removed from the premiere of her seminal HBO series ‘Girls,’ this new and—as always—brutally honest account of her life in the spotlight is a searing indictment of “success” and the damage it has done to her.
“I wrote a book that’s about listening to my own needs and instincts, not becoming a servant to this larger industrial force that will swallow you up,” Dunham tells @lottejeffs. “And yet, even all of these experiences couldn’t quell my love for doing the thing that I do, which is telling stories.”
That contradiction—ambition versus self-preservation—is the central tension of ‘Famesick,’ a gossipy and splashy romp in the tradition of all good celebrity memoirs, but with the authenticity and emotion you won’t get from your standard ghost-written A-lister tome. In a new interview, Dunham looks back at life in her early 20s, when she was the messy millennial with the Midas touch—and then everything that came after. Read the full story at the link in bio.

@Madonna riaccende il dancefloor. Con l’annuncio di “Confessions On A Dance Floor: Part II”, in arrivo il 3 luglio 2026. C’è qualcosa di potentissimo nel modo in cui la Regina del pop continua a riscrivere se stessa senza mai inseguire nessuno. Tutti cambiano era. Lei crea ancora l’evento. Confessions non è solo un titolo che ha segnato un’intera generazione: è un’attitude, un’estetica, un modo di abitare la musica e trasformarla in immaginario.
